H0.text: Cell, tissue, organ, organ system is the correct sequence of levels of organization for multicellular organisms.

H1.text: Tissue -> organ -> cell -> organ system is the correct sequence of levels of organization for multicellular organisms.

H2.text: Organ system → organ → cell → tissue is the correct sequence of levels of organization for multicellular organisms.

H3.text: Cell → organ → tissue → organ system is the sequence representing the levels of organization for multicellular organisms.

A4.text: Each level in the hierarchy can be described by its lower levels. For example, the organism may be described at any of its component levels, including the atomic, molecular, cellular, histological (tissue), organ and organ system levels.

A5.text: An organism can not be organized at the histological (tissue) level if it is not composed of tissues in the first place.
